The ACC and AHA have acknowledged the importance of value in health care and have called for eventual development of a Level of Value for clinical practice recommendations (S1.4-2). Available cost-effectiveness data were determined to be sufÔ¨Åcient to support 2 speciÔ¨Åc recommendations in this guideline (see Sections 7.1.1 and 7.1.2). As a result, a Level of Value was assigned to those 2 recommendations on the basis of the ‚ÄúACC/AHA Statement on Cost/Value Methodology in Clinical Practice Guidelines and Performance Measures,‚Äù as shown in Table 3 (S1.4-2). Available quality of life (QoL) data were deemed to be insufÔ¨Åcient to support speciÔ¨Åc recommendations in this guideline.
1.2. Organization of the Writing Committee The writing committee consisted of cardiac electrophysiologists (including those specialized in pediatrics), general adult and pediatric cardiologists (including those specialized in critical care and acute coronary syndromes [ACS], genetic cardiology, heart failure, and cost-effectiveness analyses), a geriatrician with expertise in terminal care and shared decision-making, and a lay representative, in addition to representatives from the ACC, AHA, HRS, and the Heart Failure Society of America (HFSA).
1.3. Document Review and Approval This document was reviewed by 2 ofÔ¨Åcial reviewers nominated by the ACC, AHA, and HRS; 1 ofÔ¨Åcial lay reviewer nominated by the AHA; 1 organizational reviewer nominated by the HFSA; and 28 individual content reviewers. Reviewers‚Äô RWI information was distributed to the writing committee and is published in this document (Appendix 2).

Heart Rhythm, Vol 15, No 10, October 2018
This document was approved for publication by the governing bodies of the ACC, the AHA, and the HRS; and endorsed by the HFSA.
1.4. Scope of the Guideline The purpose of this AHA/ACC/HRS document is to provide a contemporary guideline for the management of adults who have VA or who are at risk for SCD, including diseases and syndromes associated with a risk of SCD from VA. This guideline supersedes the ‚ÄúACC/AHA/ESC 2006 Guidelines for Management of Patients With Ventricular Arrhythmias and the Prevention of Sudden Cardiac Death‚Äù (S1.4-4). It also supersedes some sections of the ‚ÄúACC/AHA/HRS 2008 Guidelines for Device-Based Therapy of Cardiac Rhythm Abnormalities‚Äù (S1.4-5), speciÔ¨Åcally those sections on indications for the implantable cardioverter-deÔ¨Åbrillator (ICD); and, it updates the SCD prevention recommendations in the ‚Äú2011 ACCF/AHA Guideline for the Diagnosis and Treatment of Hypertrophic Cardiomyopathy‚Äù (S1.4-6). Some recommendations from the earlier guidelines have been updated as warranted by new evidence or a better understanding of existing evidence, and irrelevant or overlapping recommendations were deleted or modiÔ¨Åed.
In the current guideline, sudden cardiac arrest (SCA) is deÔ¨Åned as the ‚Äúsudden cessation of cardiac activity so that the victim becomes unresponsive, with no normal breathing and no signs of circulation‚Äù (S1.4-7). If corrective measures are not taken rapidly, this condition progresses to SCD. Cardiac arrest is used to signify an event that can be reversed, usually by cardiopulmonary resuscitation (CPR), administration of medications and/or deÔ¨Åbrillation or cardioversion. SCA and SCD can result from causes other than VA, such as bradyarrhythmias, electromechanical dissociation, pulmonary embolism, intracranial hemorrhage, and aortic dissection; however, the scope of this document includes only SCA and SCD due to VA.
This guideline includes indications for ICDs for the treatment of VA and prevention of SCD, but it does not delve into details on individual device selection and programming, including considerations relevant to cardiac resynchronization therapy (CRT), bradycardia pacing, and hemodynamic monitoring. These important aspects of ICD management have been covered in an HRS expert consensus statement (S1.4-8). An AHA science advisory discusses the use of wearable cardioverter-deÔ¨Åbrillators (S1.4-9). The Ô¨Åndings of that document were reviewed; however, recommendations on this topic were developed independently of that document. This guideline includes indications for catheter ablation of VA, but does not provide recommendations on speciÔ¨Åc techniques or ablation technologies, which were beyond the scope of this document.
Recommendations for interventional therapies, including ablation and the implantation of devices, apply only if these therapies can be implemented by qualiÔ¨Åed clinicians, such that outcomes consistent with published literature are a reasonable expectation. The writing committee agreed that a high degree of expertise was particularly important for

Al-Khatib et al. 2017 VA/SCD Guideline
performance of catheter ablation of VA, and this point is further emphasized in relevant sections. In addition, all recommendations related to ICDs require that meaningful survival of .1 year is expected; meaningful survival means that a patient has a reasonable quality of life and functional status.
Although this document is aimed at the adult population (18 years of age) and offers no speciÔ¨Åc recommendations for pediatric patients, some of the literature on pediatric patients was examined. In some cases, the data from pediatric patients beyond infancy helped to inform this guideline.
The writing committee recognized the importance of shared decision-making and patient-centered care and, when possible, it endeavored to formulate recommendations relevant to these important concepts. The importance of a shared decision-making process in which the patient, family, and clinicians discuss risks and beneÔ¨Åts of diagnostic and treatment options and consider the patients‚Äô personal preferences is emphasized (see Section 15).

e79
In developing this guideline, the writing committee reviewed previously published guidelines and related statements. Table 4 contains a list of guidelines and statements deemed pertinent to this writing effort and is intended for use as a resource, obviating repetition of existing guideline recommendations.
During Ô¨Ånal production review of the guidelines, several recommendations were reÔ¨Åned to better reÔ¨Çect the data and current recommended medical practice. These reÔ¨Ånements were reviewed and approved by the writing committee, the Task Force, and ACC, AHA, and HRS organizational leadership. These recommendations were:
